President Uhuru Kenyatta has urged the national Treasury to consider retaining the income tax rate at 25 per cent until January 1, 2021. The president said this will further cushion Kenyans from the economic effects of the coronavirus pandemic. He spoke during the national Covid-19 Conference on Monday. Uhuru further urged the Treasury to consider retaining VAT at 14 per cent until January next year. Tax reductions were announced on March 2 to protect jobs and uncertainty for employers. Uhuru had also ordered the reduction of corporation tax and Pay As You Earn (PAYE) to be reduced from 30 per cent to 25. Both of these reforms, Uhuru said should be extended to January 1, 2021. He advised that the 100 per cent tax relief for persons earning a gross income of Sh24,000 to be maintained beyond the Sunset date of December 31, 2020. All of the reforms were officially enforced from April 28 when Uhuru signed into law the Tax Laws (Amendment) Bill, 2020 as part of measures to cushion the public against effects of Covid-19 pandemic. "To continue cushioning our Micro, Small and Medium-Sized Enterprises the National Treasury considers maintaining the reduction of the turn overtax rate from 3 per cent to 1 percent for all MSMEs," Uhuru said.